# Coder

How to build. Architecture, walks, substrate, build order, lessons.
For coordinate reference: mind/codex. For the guide on how walks
work at the byte level: compact/1/coder/guide.


## Boot Chain

  legacy/boot.asm → loads kernel, sets VESA mode (MBR, 16-bit, dies)
  legacy/x86.asm  → all substrate in one file (sealed):
    cpu      mode switch 32→64, page tables, wakes APs
    handoff  inits JIT, runs γ (genesis), enters find-work
    ƒ        JIT compiler: coordinates → x86 function
    ψ        wave byte interpreter
  genesis.w       → founding walk, assembled by hodos (runs once)
  walks/*.w       → the OS: everything that grows

ƒ and ψ dissolve on a trit processor. The walks stay.


## Encoding / Payload Boundary

  encoding (φ/μ) = equation + walker (how coordinates become x86)
  payload  (μ/φ) = everything above the walker (what coordinates mean)

Test: could this walk run unchanged on a trit processor? If no,
encoding leaked upward. Fix the encoder, not the walk.


## Walks Are Wave Bytes

  byte 0:   wave byte (2 bits per dim × 4 = 1 byte)
  [ext]:    signed i8 per extended dimension (τ,χ,μ,φ order)
  byte N:   flags byte [reserved:2][arg2:2][arg1:2][arg0:2]
  bytes:    inline args (00=pipeline, 01=u8, 10=u32, 11=u64)

Walker control (reserved bytes >= 0xFC):
  0xFE + u32 = skip_z (forward if pipeline == 0)
  0xFD + u32 = skip_nz (forward if pipeline != 0)
  0xFC + u32 = loop_back (rewind if pipeline != 0)

Width on τ: |τ|=1→qword, 3→byte, 5→word, 7→dword.
Register file on φ: |φ|=1→port, 3→MSR, 5→CPUID.


## Loops

The only data structure. 64 bytes, cache-line aligned:

  [0:7]   write cursor    (single writer — fermion)
  [8:15]  slowest reader  (for reclamation)
  [16:23] buffer address
  [24:31] depth (power of 2)
  [32:39] mask (depth - 1)
  [40:47] record size
  [48:55] scratch_a       (per-loop: reader cursor or resistance)
  [56:63] scratch_b       (per-loop: temp or identity)

Per-reader cursors. No shared mutable state. No atomics. No locks.
Read = pointer to slot (zero-copy, boson semantics).

Loop pipeline (~4+6 bonds): empty check → slot address → read at
pointer → advance cursor. Record size irrelevant to read primitive.


## Genes = Data, Walks = Code

Same walk + different gene data = different device. e1000 and virtio
are the same NIC walk with different BAR offsets. Genesis discovers
hardware, picks the gene, fills the table.


## Genesis

Runs once. Embryonic development:
  1. Bootloader wakes all cores, enters lattice_start
  2. lattice_start inits JIT, walks genesis
  3. Genesis expresses hardware genes, writes walk data into loops
  4. Genesis returns. Development ends.
  5. All cores enter find-work. No special roles.

GENESIS DOES NOT GROW. New software = new walk data in loops.
Genesis only grows for new hardware genes.


## Fill Pressure = Natural Selection

  Full loop → high demand → attracts cores
  Empty loop → no demand → releases cores

No scheduler. Fill pressure self-organizes. Optimal fill: 25%.


## Loop Registry

  loop_list[16], producer_list[16], consumer_list[16], loop_count
  Each loop has producer + consumer walks. Fill determines which to express.


## File Structure

  code/
    genesis.w          founding walk — @includes all walks
    walks/*.w          PCI, virtio, GPU, ATA, ucode, gpu_nvidia, etc.
    firmware/          CPU microcode (34 blobs) + GPU (NVIDIA TU102)
    build/             hodos.c, link.ld, run script
    legacy/            x86.asm (sealed), boot.asm (MBR)

  Build modes:
    bash build/run          GUI (KVM, MBR, VESA)
    bash build/run headless single core, multiboot, no VESA
    bash build/run kvm      MBR, KVM, display none
    bash build/run img      bare metal USB image

  %ifdef DEBUG wraps all debugcon bonds.


